<section class="home-section">
  <p class="section-eyebrow">The journey</p>
  <h2>Built as I learned it</h2>
  <div class="prose">
    <p>This started in high school calculus. I got fixated on complex functions — the idea that you could do calculus on numbers that aren't even real — and wanted to know what a complex derivative actually <em>does</em>. I didn't have the background to chase it down yet; calc I and II weren't enough. Multivariable and vector calculus finally gave me the tools, and this summer I went back and answered the questions that had been sitting there for years: what does integrating over the complex plane even mean, why do the Cauchy-Riemann equations decide whether a function is holomorphic.</p>
    <p>I'm Max — an incoming math major at UCSB's College of Creative Studies. This site isn't trying to be a textbook; good ones already exist. It's the record of one path through the subject — the lessons as I actually learned them, in order, using Claude as a Socratic tutor.</p>
    <p>The system behind it — session structure, spaced review, a running profile of how I learn, and the actual prompts that commissioned each visualization — is written up in <a href="/how-i-built-this/">How I built this</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

